2)  Entry verification 
 

Deployment data are uploaded from the YSI data logger to a Personal Computer (IBM compatible).  Files are exported from EcoWatch in a comma-delimited format (.CDF), EcoWatch Lite in a comma separated file (CSV) or KOR Software in an Excel File (.XLS) and uploaded to the CDMO where they undergo automated primary QAQC; automated depth/level corrections for changes in barometric pressure (cDepth or cLevel parameters); and become part of the CDMO’s online provisional database.  All pre- and post-deployment data are removed from the file prior to upload.  During primary QAQC, data are flagged if they are missing or out of sensor range.  The edited file is then returned to the Reserve for secondary QAQC where it is opened in Microsoft Excel and processed using the CDMO’s NERRQAQC Excel macro.  The macro inserts station codes, creates metadata worksheets for flagged data and summary statistics, and graphs the data for review.  It allows the user to apply QAQC flags and codes to the data, remove any overlapping deployment data, append files, and export the resulting data file for upload to the CDMO.  Upload after secondary QAQC results in ingestion into the database as provisional plus data, recalculation of cDepth or cLevel parameters, and finally tertiary QAQC by the CDMO and assimilation into the CDMO’s authoritative online database.  Where deployment overlap occurs between files, the data produced by the newly calibrated sonde is generally accepted as being the most accurate.  For more information on QAQC flags and codes, see Sections 11 and 12. Anna Deck was responsible for 2017 data management.

 

 
3)  Research objectives 
 
Four long-term monitoring stations have been established along the salinity gradient of the San Francisco Bay estuary in order to collect essential baseline information and improve our understanding of the responses of water quality to tidal dynamics and watershed inputs. These San Francisco Bay National Estuarine Research Reserve (SFB NERR) System-Wide Monitoring Program (SWMP) stations collect a variety of data to address three primary topics: 1) Short-term variability and long-term changes in estuarine water parameters within different regions of the estuary (e.g., patterns associated with localized impacts of seasonal storm events, variability in water quality parameters associated with diurnal and seasonal patterns of primary productivity, inter-annual differences in rainfall, spatial extent of oceanic and tidal forcing, magnitude and influence of El Niño – La Niña events, and long-term changes associated with the Pacific Decadal Oscillation and sea-level rise); 2) Anthropogenic disturbance caused by land use changes including population migration, urbanization, wastewater inputs and proximity of livestock and grazing areas; and 3) Integration of these data into the broader Central and Northern California Ocean Observing System (CeNCOOS) in order to provide much needed inland and shallow water data to complement the extensive, deep-water and offshore data currently available  through CeNCOOS. Together these SWMP data provide a framework for understanding the environmental conditions and ecological processes of San Francisco Bay. 
 
4)  Research methods 
 

YSI 6600 or EXO multiparameter sondes are deployed at four monitoring sites and are programmed to record pH, temperature, specific conductivity, salinity, depth, turbidity, and dissolved oxygen every 15 minutes for a maximum of 28 consecutive days in a single deployment.  Prior to deployment, calibration and maintenance are performed on each sonde and probe following the manufacturer's instructions (YSI EXO or 6-series operations manual).  The solutions used for each probe are as follows; conductivity and salinity is YSI solution 3168 (10,000 μS/cm), pH is YSI solution 3822 pH 7 and YSI 3823 pH 10, turbidity is 0 NTU (deionized water) and 124 FNU / 126 NTU solution YSI 607300.  Until March 2011, a 0.5 NTU offset was used to minimize negative turbidity readings. Lastly, the depth sensor is calibrated in air using a depth offset value determined by the current barometric pressure as measured by a YSI handheld device.  Following calibration, sondes are run in aerated freshwater for several days. These pre-deployment data undergo a quality assurance process to ensure consistent, high quality calibrations before sondes are deployed. Several methods are used to minimize fouling on the probes when deployed. The optical probes (dissolved oxygen and turbidity) have wipers that clean probe faces before taking a reading and the pH probe is either wiped with a brush attached to one of the optical probes or may be sprayed with YSI Cspray.

 

One sonde is deployed at each of the permanent SWMP stations at approximately 0.25 – 0.5 m above the substrate. Throughout the year, all data are recorded in Pacific Standard Time.  During transport, each sonde is wrapped in a tap-water-soaked towel and placed horizontally in a large cooler for insulation against jarring and to prevent drying of probes. At swap out and as close to the 15-minute sonde recording time as possible, a handheld YSI Pro Plus is used to record dissolved oxygen, salinity, specific conductivity, pH, and temperature near the location of the sonde as a quality assurance check.  Additionally, the sonde being deployed is first hung near the sonde being retrieved to collect one or two overlapping data points to allow for direct comparisons between the two consecutively deployed sondes.  The sondes are lowered by cable into protective cases constructed from 5"-diameter ABS plumbing pipe.  A 7/16” stainless steel bolt across the bottom prevents the sonde from falling out of the ABS pipe and ensures that the sonde monitors conditions at the same depth with every deployment.  The ABS pipes were previously coated with a thin coat of Ultralux Micron Extra antifouling paint or black West Marine Bottom Shield antifouling paint.  Numerous two inch or larger holes were cut into the ABS tubes to provide for tidal flushing in order to expose the probes to ambient water conditions.  The pipes were affixed vertically to stable log pilings using stainless steel chain and HDPE bindings that hold the pipe at a fixed distance away from the piling. In 2005 and 2006, all YSI sensors and sonde guards were painted with the anti-fouling paint according to procedures outlined in the YSI manual.  This treatment was stopped later in 2006 because fouling of submerged equipment was determined to be low, although some residual paint remains on equipment we deploy today.

 

At the end of each deployment period, retrieved sondes are again wrapped in a water-saturated towel and placed in a cooler for transport back to the lab.  The sondes are carefully cleaned with hot soapy water using caution not to clean the probe faces, the specific conductivity chambers, or the depth sensor hole in an effort to minimally affect post-calibration numbers.  They are then placed in a bucket with oxygen saturated water overnight to provide another quality assurance opportunity.  Post-deployment calibrations are performed within 24 hours of retrieval to determine if instrument drift has occurred and to evaluate the validity of the data.  In conjunction with post-deployment calibrations, the data are uploaded to a desktop computer via a flying lead cable. Graphs of each parameter are generated and examined to identify significant problems or events. These data are then uploaded to the CDMO website for primary QAQC. Sonde cleaning of the dissolved oxygen, conductivity, depth, pH, and turbidity probes are performed as outlined in the YSI manual prior to the next calibration.  

 

A Sutron Sat-Link2 transmitter was installed at the China Camp station in 2006 and transmits data to the NOAA GOES satellite, NESDIS ID #3B02741E. A Sutron Sat-Link2 transmitter was installed at the Gallinas Creek station on 03/11/2013 and transmits data to the NOAA GOES satellite, NESDIS ID #3B0513CC. A Sutron Sat-Link2 transmitter was installed at the First Mallard station on 3/13/2013 and transmits data to the NOAA GOES satellite, NESDIS ID #3B04E1B2. A Sutron Sat-Link2 transmitter was installed at the Second Mallard station on 03/12/2013 and transmits data to the NOAA GOES satellite, NESDIS ID #3B0500BA.  The transmissions are scheduled hourly and contain four (4) data sets reflecting fifteen minute data sampling intervals.  Upon receipt by the CDMO, the data undergoes the same automated primary QAQC process detailed in Section 2 above.  The “real-time” telemetry data become part of the provisional dataset until undergoing secondary and tertiary QAQC and assimilation in the CDMO’s authoritative online database.  Provisional and authoritative data are available at http://cdmo.baruch.sc.edu.

 
5)  Site location and character 
 
The San Francisco Estuary includes several embayments located downstream of the confluence of the Sacramento and San Joaquin Rivers and has the largest watershed on the west coast. The four main embayments in this system are the Central Bay (or San Francisco Bay), South Bay, San Pablo Bay and Suisun Bay. China Camp State Park is located on San Pablo Bay and Rush Ranch Open Space Preserve is located within the western portion of Suisun Marsh extending north of Suisun Bay.  With these two sites, the SF Bay NERR covers approximately 3,700 acres that encompass 1,150 acres of tidal marsh. 
 
China Camp (38° 0' 4.49 N, 122° 27' 37.28 W) and Gallinas Creek (38° 00' 57.3 N, 122° 30' 30.6 W)
The China Camp monitoring station (CC) is located within China Camp State Park in western San Pablo Bay and captures water quality information most representative of the marine-influenced portion of the estuary. The station consists of a sonde mounted near the end of a historic pier in a semi-pristine area with minimal upland development and serves as a reference site for the saline portion of the estuary.  Along with freshwater outflow from the Sacramento and San Joaquin Rivers, the CC station experiences a mix of freshwater runoff from forested uplands and developed low-lying areas with road runoff as an important pollutant.  The sonde is positioned above soft silt clay sediments that exhibit strong seasonal fluctuations in erosion and deposition. The typical monthly average salinity ranges from 10 to 29 psu, and the average salinity is approximately 23 psu. This station experiences a tidal range as referenced from the 2012 NOAA tide predictions for “Point San Pedro” of approximately -0.5 to 2.1 m relative to MLLW, and measures water depth from approximately 0 to 2.52 m. At very low tides the sonde at this site samples in an isolated puddle of water and sometimes comes out of water. The pipe was vertically repositioned at a higher depth in December 2015 (with additional adjustments in February 2016) and replaced with an updated pipe design that allows for improved water flow around sensors. Please see additional comments at the end of this document (Section 14).
The Gallinas Creek monitoring station (GC) is located in a small tidal creek that meets San Pablo Bay just outside the northern boundary of the reserve at China Camp State Park.  Draining both forest uplands and developed low-lying areas, Gallinas Creek is relatively heavily impacted by upstream wastewater discharge, urban development lining one edge of the creek and natural vegetation lining much of the other side. The GC sonde is affixed to a piling within the channel and positioned above soft silt clay sediments. , The range of monthly average salinity is about 6 to 31 psu, and the average salinity is approximately 21 psu.  It experiences a tidal range as referenced from the 2012 NOAA tide predictions for “Gallinas, Gallinas Creek” of approximately -0.5 to 2.1 m relative to MLLW, and measures water depth from approximately 0.59 to 3.13 m.
 
First (38° 11' 41.70 N, 122° 1' 58.02 W) and Second Mallard (38° 11' 02.8 N, 122° 0' 48.9 W)
Rush Ranch Open Space Preserve is located in the brackish portion of the estuary in western Suisun Marsh north of Suisun Bay. It includes tidal brackish high-plain marsh, defined by two main tidal creeks, First Mallard Slough and Second Mallard Slough. The monitoring stations within Rush Ranch are located where these two sloughs each intersect with Cutoff Slough, a major offshoot of Suisun Slough connecting to Montezuma Slough and ultimately to Suisun Bay. First Mallard Slough innervates the northwestern portion of Rush Ranch, whereas Second Mallard Slough drains the southeastern areas.  Freshwater input is influenced by the larger watershed of the San Francisco Estuary, water control practices in Suisun Marsh (primarily aimed at regulating salinity in managed duck ponds), and localized runoff from the Potrero Hills and immediately adjacent uplands into First Mallard Slough. Known inputs of pollutants and nutrients at Rush Ranch include runoff from roads, ranchlands, regional wastewater discharge, and localized boating and hunting.  For both stations, the range of monthly average salinity is about 0 to 12 psu, and the average salinity is approximately 5 psu. The typical tidal range as referenced from the 2012 NOAA tide predictions for “Montezuma Slough Bridge” is approximately -0.3 to 1.8 m relative to MLLW. First Mallard station measures water depth of approximately 0.66 to 2.94 m and Second Mallard station measures water depth of approximately 0.82 to 3.10 m.

6)  Data collection period

7)  Distribution

 

NOAA retains the right to analyze, synthesize and publish summaries of the NERRS System-wide Monitoring Program data.  The NERRS retains the right to be fully credited for having collected and process the data.  Following academic courtesy standards, the NERR site where the data were collected should be contacted and fully acknowledged in any subsequent publications in which any part of the data are used.  The data set enclosed within this package/transmission is only as good as the quality assurance and quality control procedures outlined by the enclosed metadata reporting statement.  The user bears all responsibility for its subsequent use/misuse in any further analyses or comparisons.  The Federal government does not assume liability to the Recipient or third persons, nor will the Federal government reimburse or indemnify the Recipient for its liability due to any losses resulting in any way from the use of this data.

 

Requested citation format:

NOAA National Estuarine Research Reserve System (NERRS). System-wide Monitoring Program. Data accessed from the NOAA NERRS Centralized Data Management Office website: http://www.nerrsdata.org/; accessed 12 October 2012.

 

NERR water quality data and metadata can be obtained from the Research Coordinator at the individual NERR site (please see Principal Investigators and Contact Persons), from the Data Manager at the Centralized Data Management Office (please see personnel directory under the general information link on the CDMO home page) and online at the CDMO home page www.nerrsdata.org.  Data are available in comma delimited format. 

 

8)  Associated researchers and projects 
 

In addition to water quality monitoring with YSI 6600 and EXO sondes, SFB NERR monitors 15-minute meteorological conditions at Rush Ranch and dissolved nutrients with monthly grab samples and diel sampling at all four sonde stations which may be correlated with this water quality dataset. These data are available at www.nerrsdata.org. Reserve staff also regularly monitors benthic invertebrates and marsh vegetation, with plans to expand these efforts over the coming years.

Depth Qualifier:

The NERR System-Wide Monitoring Program utilizes YSI data sondes that can be equipped with either vented or non-vented depth/level sensors.  Readings for both vented and non-vented sensors are automatically compensated for water density change due to variations in temperature and salinity; but for all non-vented depth measurements, changes in atmospheric pressure between calibrations appear as changes in water depth.  The error is equal to approximately 1.02 cm for every 1 millibar change in atmospheric pressure, and is eliminated for vented sensors because they are vented to the atmosphere throughout the deployment time interval. 

 

Beginning in 2006, NERR SWMP standard calibration protocol calls for all non-vented depth sensors to read 0 meters at a (local) barometric pressure of 1013.25 mb (760 mm/hg).  To achieve this, each site calibrates their depth sensor with a depth offset number, which is calculated using the actual atmospheric pressure at the time of calibration and the equation provided in the SWMP calibration sheet or digital calibration log.  This offset procedure standardizes each depth calibration for the entire NERR System.  If accurate atmospheric pressure data are available, non-vented sensor depth measurements at any NERR can be corrected.

 

In 2010, the CDMO began automatically correcting depth/level data for changes in barometric pressure as measured by the Reserve’s associated meteorological station during data ingestion.  These corrected depth/level data are reported as cDepth and cLevel, and are assigned QAQC flags and codes based on QAQC protocols.  Please see sections 11 and 12 for QAQC flag and code definitions.

 

NOTE:  older depth data cannot be corrected without verifying that the depth offset was in place and whether a vented or non-vented depth sensor was in use.  No SWMP data prior to 2006 can be corrected using this method.  The following equation is used for corrected depth/level data provided by the CDMO beginning in 2010:

((1013-BP)*0.0102)+Depth/Level = cDepth/cLevel.

 

Salinity Units Qualifier:

 

In 2013, EXO sondes were approved for SWMP use and began to be utilized by Reserves. While the 6600 series sondes report salinity in parts per thousand (ppt) units, the EXO sondes report practical salinity units (psu). These units are essentially the same and for SWMP purposes are understood to be equivalent, however psu is considered the more appropriate designation. Moving forward the NERR System will assign psu salinity units for all data regardless of sonde type.

 

Turbidity Qualifier:

 

In 2013, EXO sondes were approved for SWMP use and began to be utilized by Reserves. While the 6600 series sondes report turbidity in nephelometric turbidity units (NTU), the EXO sondes use formazin nephelometric units (FNU). These units are essentially the same but indicate a difference in sensor methodology, for SWMP purposes they will be considered equivalent.  Moving forward, the NERR System will use FNU/NTU as the designated units for all turbidity data regardless of sonde type. If turbidity units and sensor methodology are of concern, please see the Sensor Specifications portion of the metadata.

 

Chlorophyll Fluorescence Disclaimer:

YSI chlorophyll sensors (6025 or 599102-01) are designed to serve as a proxy for chlorophyll concentrations in the field for monitoring applications and complement traditional lab extraction methods; therefore, there are accuracy limitations associated with the data that are detailed in the YSI manual including interference from other fluorescent species, differences in calibration method, and effects of cell structure, particle size, organism type, temperature, and light on sensor measurements.

11)  QAQC flag definitions 

 
QAQC flags provide documentation of the data and are applied to individual data points by insertion into the parameter’s associated flag column (header preceded by an F_).   During primary automated QAQC (performed by the CDMO), -5, -4, and -2 flags are applied automatically to indicate data that is missing and above or below sensor range.  All remaining data are then flagged 0, passing initial QAQC checks.   During secondary and tertiary QAQC 1, -3, and 5 flags may be used to note data as suspect, rejected due to QAQC, or corrected.
 
-5 Outside High Sensor Range
-4 Outside Low Sensor Range
-3                Data Rejected due to QAQC
-2                Missing Data
-1                Optional SWMP Supported Parameter
 0                Data Passed Initial QAQC Checks
 1                Suspect Data
 2                Open - reserved for later flag
 3                Calculated data: non-vented depth/level sensor correction for changes in barometric pressure
 4                Historical Data:  Pre-Auto QAQC
 5                Corrected Data
 
12)  QAQC code definitions 
 
QAQC codes are used in conjunction with QAQC flags to provide further documentation of the data and are also applied by insertion into the associated flag column.  There are three (3) different code categories, general, sensor, and comment.  General errors document general problems with the deployment or YSI datasonde, sensor errors are sensor specific, and comment codes are used to further document conditions or a problem with the data.  Only one general or sensor error and one comment code can be applied to a particular data point, but some comment codes (marked with an * below) can be applied to the entire record in the F_Record column.  
 
General Errors

      GIC         No instrument deployed due to ice

      GIM        Instrument malfunction

      GIT         Instrument recording error; recovered telemetry data

      GMC       No instrument deployed due to maintenance/calibration

      GNF       Deployment tube clogged / no flow

      GOW      Out of water event

      GPF        Power failure / low battery

      GQR       Data rejected due to QA/QC checks

      GSM       See metadata

   Corrected Depth/Level Data Codes

      GCC        Calculated with data that were corrected during QA/QC

      GCM       Calculated value could not be determined due to missing data

      GCR        Calculated value could not be determined due to rejected data

      GCS        Calculated value suspect due to questionable data

      GCU       Calculated value could not be determined due to unavailable data

 

Sensor Errors

      SBO        Blocked optic

      SCF         Conductivity sensor failure

      SCS         Chlorophyll spike

      SDF        Depth port frozen

      SDG        Suspect due to sensor diagnostics

      SDO        DO suspect

      SDP        DO membrane puncture

      SIC          Incorrect calibration / contaminated standard

      SNV        Negative value

      SOW       Sensor out of water

      SPC         Post calibration out of range

      SQR        Data rejected due to QAQC checks

      SSD         Sensor drift

      SSM        Sensor malfunction

      SSR          Sensor removed / not deployed

      STF         Catastrophic temperature sensor failure

      STS         Turbidity spike

      SWM       Wiper malfunction / loss

 

Comments

      CAB*       Algal bloom

      CAF        Acceptable calibration/accuracy error of sensor

      CAP        Depth sensor in water, affected by atmospheric pressure

      CBF         Biofouling

      CCU        Cause unknown

      CDA*      DO hypoxia (<3 mg/L)

      CDB*      Disturbed bottom

      CDF        Data appear to fit conditions

      CFK*       Fish kill

      CIP *       Surface ice present at sample station

      CLT*       Low tide

      CMC*      In field maintenance/cleaning

      CMD*     Mud in probe guard

      CND       New deployment begins

      CRE*       Significant rain event

      CSM*      See metadata

      CTS         Turbidity spike

      CVT*       Possible vandalism/tampering

      CWD*     Data collected at wrong depth

      CWE*      Significant weather event

14)  Other remarks/notes 
 

Data are missing due to equipment or associated specific probes not being deployed, equipment failure, time of maintenance or calibration of equipment, or repair/replacement of a sampling station platform.  Any NANs in the dataset stand for “not a number” and are the result of low power, disconnected wires, or out of range readings.  If additional information on missing data is needed, contact the Research Coordinator at the reserve submitting the data.

 

China Camp

At very low tides the sonde at this site samples in an isolated puddle of water and sometimes comes out of water.

2)  Entry verification 
 

Deployment data are uploaded from the YSI data logger to a Personal Computer (IBM compatible).  Files are exported from EcoWatch in a comma-delimited format (.CDF), EcoWatch Lite in a comma separated file (CSV) or KOR Software in an Excel File (.XLS) and uploaded to the CDMO where they undergo automated primary QAQC; automated depth/level corrections for changes in barometric pressure (cDepth or cLevel parameters); and become part of the CDMO’s online provisional database.  All pre- and post-deployment data are removed from the file prior to upload.  During primary QAQC, data are flagged if they are missing or out of sensor range.  The edited file is then returned to the Reserve for secondary QAQC where it is opened in Microsoft Excel and processed using the CDMO’s NERRQAQC Excel macro.  The macro inserts station codes, creates metadata worksheets for flagged data and summary statistics, and graphs the data for review.  It allows the user to apply QAQC flags and codes to the data, remove any overlapping deployment data, append files, and export the resulting data file for upload to the CDMO.  Upload after secondary QAQC results in ingestion into the database as provisional plus data, recalculation of cDepth or cLevel parameters, and finally tertiary QAQC by the CDMO and assimilation into the CDMO’s authoritative online database.  Where deployment overlap occurs between files, the data produced by the newly calibrated sonde is generally accepted as being the most accurate.  For more information on QAQC flags and codes, see Sections 11 and 12. Anna Deck was responsible for 2018 data management.

 
3)  Research objectives 
 
Four long-term monitoring stations have been established along the salinity gradient of the San Francisco Bay estuary in order to collect essential baseline information and improve our understanding of the responses of water quality to tidal dynamics and watershed inputs. These San Francisco Bay National Estuarine Research Reserve (SFB NERR) System-Wide Monitoring Program (SWMP) stations collect a variety of data to address three primary topics: 1) Short-term variability and long-term changes in estuarine water parameters within different regions of the estuary (e.g., patterns associated with localized impacts of seasonal storm events, variability in water quality parameters associated with diurnal and seasonal patterns of primary productivity, inter-annual differences in rainfall, spatial extent of oceanic and tidal forcing, magnitude and influence of El Niño – La Niña events, and long-term changes associated with the Pacific Decadal Oscillation and sea-level rise); 2) Anthropogenic disturbance caused by land use changes including population migration, urbanization, wastewater inputs and proximity of livestock and grazing areas; and 3) Integration of these data into the broader Central and Northern California Ocean Observing System (CeNCOOS) in order to provide much needed inland and shallow water data to complement the extensive, deep-water and offshore data currently available  through CeNCOOS. Together these SWMP data provide a framework for understanding the environmental conditions and ecological processes of San Francisco Bay. 
 
4)  Research methods 
 

YSI 6600 or EXO multiparameter sondes are deployed at four monitoring sites and are programmed to record pH, temperature, specific conductivity, salinity, depth, turbidity, and dissolved oxygen every 15 minutes for a maximum of 28 consecutive days in a single deployment.  Prior to deployment, calibration and maintenance are performed on each sonde and probe following the manufacturer's instructions (YSI EXO or 6-series operations manual).  The solutions used for each probe are as follows; conductivity and salinity is YSI solution 3168 (10,000 μS/cm), pH is YSI solution 3822 pH 7 and YSI 3823 pH 10, turbidity is 0 NTU (deionized water) and 124 FNU / 126 NTU solution YSI 607300.  Until March 2011, a 0.5 NTU offset was used to minimize negative turbidity readings. Lastly, the depth sensor is calibrated in air using a depth offset value determined by the current barometric pressure as measured by a YSI handheld device.  Following calibration, sondes are run in aerated freshwater for several days. These pre-deployment data undergo a quality assurance process to ensure consistent, high quality calibrations before sondes are deployed. Several methods are used to minimize fouling on the probes when deployed. The optical probes (dissolved oxygen and turbidity) have wipers that clean probe faces before taking a reading and the pH probe is either wiped with a brush attached to one of the optical probes or may be sprayed with YSI Cspray.

 

One sonde is deployed at each of the permanent SWMP stations at approximately 0.25 – 0.5 m above the substrate. Throughout the year, all data are recorded in Pacific Standard Time.  During transport, each sonde is wrapped in a tap-water-soaked towel and placed horizontally in a large cooler for insulation against jarring and to prevent drying of probes. At swap out and as close to the 15-minute sonde recording time as possible, a handheld YSI Pro Plus is used to record dissolved oxygen, salinity, specific conductivity, pH, and temperature near the location of the sonde as a quality assurance check.  Additionally, the sonde being deployed is first hung near the sonde being retrieved to collect one or two overlapping data points to allow for direct comparisons between the two consecutively deployed sondes.  The sondes are lowered by cable into protective cases constructed from 5"-diameter ABS plumbing pipe.  A 7/16” stainless steel bolt across the bottom prevents the sonde from falling out of the ABS pipe and ensures that the sonde monitors conditions at the same depth with every deployment.  The ABS pipes were previously coated with a thin coat of Ultralux Micron Extra antifouling paint or black West Marine Bottom Shield antifouling paint.  Numerous two inch or larger holes were cut into the ABS tubes to provide for tidal flushing in order to expose the probes to ambient water conditions.  The pipes were affixed vertically to stable log pilings using stainless steel chain and HDPE bindings that hold the pipe at a fixed distance away from the piling. In 2005 and 2006, all YSI sensors and sonde guards were painted with the anti-fouling paint according to procedures outlined in the YSI manual.  This treatment was stopped later in 2006 because fouling of submerged equipment was determined to be low, although some residual paint remains on equipment we deploy today.

 

At the end of each deployment period, retrieved sondes are again wrapped in a water-saturated towel and placed in a cooler for transport back to the lab.  The sondes are carefully cleaned with hot soapy water using caution not to clean the probe faces, the specific conductivity chambers, or the depth sensor hole in an effort to minimally affect post-calibration numbers.  They are then placed in a bucket with oxygen saturated water overnight to provide another quality assurance opportunity.  Post-deployment calibrations are performed within 24 hours of retrieval to determine if instrument drift has occurred and to evaluate the validity of the data.  In conjunction with post-deployment calibrations, the data are uploaded to a desktop computer via a flying lead cable. Graphs of each parameter are generated and examined to identify significant problems or events. These data are then uploaded to the CDMO website for primary QAQC. Sonde cleaning of the dissolved oxygen, conductivity, depth, pH, and turbidity probes are performed as outlined in the YSI manual prior to the next calibration.  

 

A Sutron Sat-Link2 transmitter was installed at the China Camp station in 2006 and transmits data to the NOAA GOES satellite, NESDIS ID #3B02741E. A Sutron Sat-Link2 transmitter was installed at the Gallinas Creek station on 03/11/2013 and transmits data to the NOAA GOES satellite, NESDIS ID #3B0513CC. A Sutron Sat-Link2 transmitter was installed at the First Mallard station on 3/13/2013 and transmits data to the NOAA GOES satellite, NESDIS ID #3B04E1B2. A Sutron Sat-Link2 transmitter was installed at the Second Mallard station on 03/12/2013 and transmits data to the NOAA GOES satellite, NESDIS ID #3B0500BA.  The transmissions are scheduled hourly and contain four (4) data sets reflecting fifteen minute data sampling intervals.  Upon receipt by the CDMO, the data undergoes the same automated primary QAQC process detailed in Section 2 above.  The “real-time” telemetry data become part of the provisional dataset until undergoing secondary and tertiary QAQC and assimilation in the CDMO’s authoritative online database.  Provisional and authoritative data are available at http://cdmo.baruch.sc.edu.

 
 5)  Site location and character 
 
The San Francisco Estuary includes several embayments located downstream of the confluence of the Sacramento and San Joaquin Rivers and has the largest watershed on the west coast. The four main embayments in this system are the Central Bay (or San Francisco Bay), South Bay, San Pablo Bay and Suisun Bay. China Camp State Park is located on San Pablo Bay and Rush Ranch Open Space Preserve is located within the western portion of Suisun Marsh extending north of Suisun Bay.  With these two sites, the SF Bay NERR covers approximately 3,700 acres that encompass 1,150 acres of tidal marsh. 
 
China Camp (38° 0' 4.49 N, 122° 27' 37.28 W) and Gallinas Creek (38° 00' 57.3 N, 122° 30' 30.6 W)
The China Camp monitoring station (CC) is located within China Camp State Park in western San Pablo Bay and captures water quality information most representative of the marine-influenced portion of the estuary. The station consists of a sonde mounted near the end of a historic pier in a semi-pristine area with minimal upland development and serves as a reference site for the saline portion of the estuary.  Along with freshwater outflow from the Sacramento and San Joaquin Rivers, the CC station experiences a mix of freshwater runoff from forested uplands and developed low-lying areas with road runoff as an important pollutant.  The sonde is positioned above soft silt clay sediments that exhibit strong seasonal fluctuations in erosion and deposition. The typical monthly average salinity ranges from 10 to 29 psu, and the average salinity is approximately 23 psu. This station experiences a tidal range as referenced from the 2012 NOAA tide predictions for “Point San Pedro” of approximately -0.5 to 2.1 m relative to MLLW, and measures water depth from approximately 0 to 2.52 m. At very low tides the sonde at this site samples in an isolated puddle of water and sometimes comes out of water. The pipe was vertically repositioned at a higher depth in December 2015 (with additional adjustments in February 2016) and replaced with an updated pipe design that allows for improved water flow around sensors. Please see additional comments at the end of this document (Section 14).
The Gallinas Creek monitoring station (GC) is located in a small tidal creek that meets San Pablo Bay just outside the northern boundary of the reserve at China Camp State Park.  Draining both forest uplands and developed low-lying areas, Gallinas Creek is relatively heavily impacted by upstream wastewater discharge, urban development lining one edge of the creek and natural vegetation lining much of the other side. The GC sonde is affixed to a piling within the channel and positioned above soft silt clay sediments. , The range of monthly average salinity is about 6 to 31 psu, and the average salinity is approximately 21 psu.  It experiences a tidal range as referenced from the 2012 NOAA tide predictions for “Gallinas, Gallinas Creek” of approximately -0.5 to 2.1 m relative to MLLW, and measures water depth from approximately 0.59 to 3.13 m.
 
First (38° 11' 41.70 N, 122° 1' 58.02 W) and Second Mallard (38° 11' 02.8 N, 122° 0' 48.9 W)
Rush Ranch Open Space Preserve is located in the brackish portion of the estuary in western Suisun Marsh north of Suisun Bay. It includes tidal brackish high-plain marsh, defined by two main tidal creeks, First Mallard Slough and Second Mallard Slough. The monitoring stations within Rush Ranch are located where these two sloughs each intersect with Cutoff Slough, a major offshoot of Suisun Slough connecting to Montezuma Slough and ultimately to Suisun Bay. First Mallard Slough innervates the northwestern portion of Rush Ranch, whereas Second Mallard Slough drains the southeastern areas.  Freshwater input is influenced by the larger watershed of the San Francisco Estuary, water control practices in Suisun Marsh (primarily aimed at regulating salinity in managed duck ponds), and localized runoff from the Potrero Hills and immediately adjacent uplands into First Mallard Slough. Known inputs of pollutants and nutrients at Rush Ranch include runoff from roads, ranchlands, regional wastewater discharge, and localized boating and hunting.  For both stations, the range of monthly average salinity is about 0 to 12 psu, and the average salinity is approximately 5 psu. The typical tidal range as referenced from the 2012 NOAA tide predictions for “Montezuma Slough Bridge” is approximately -0.3 to 1.8 m relative to MLLW. First Mallard station measures water depth of approximately 0.66 to 2.94 m and Second Mallard station measures water depth of approximately 0.82 to 3.10 m.

6)  Data collection period 
 

As stated above water-quality sampling at the China Camp pier (CC) began in March 2005. Sampling at Gallinas Creek (GC) began in December 2005, ceased in December 2006 due to a boating accident resulting in loss of infrastructure for sonde mount, and resumed again in May 2008. First Mallard (FM) and Second Mallard (SM) commenced sampling in May 2008. The sonde configuration column clarifies variation in configuration. All 6600 series sondes had the same sensor configuration (see Section 9), and sonde model is noted (V2-4). EXO2 sondes (E2) were deployed with identical turbidity, central wiper, and dissolved oxygen probes. Either standard (CT2) or wiped (WCT) conductivity-temperature probes were used, and either guarded (G) or unguarded (U) pH probes were used. These variations are denoted below.

7)  Distribution

 

NOAA retains the right to analyze, synthesize and publish summaries of the NERRS System-wide Monitoring Program data.  The NERRS retains the right to be fully credited for having collected and process the data.  Following academic courtesy standards, the NERR site where the data were collected should be contacted and fully acknowledged in any subsequent publications in which any part of the data are used.  The data set enclosed within this package/transmission is only as good as the quality assurance and quality control procedures outlined by the enclosed metadata reporting statement.  The user bears all responsibility for its subsequent use/misuse in any further analyses or comparisons.  The Federal government does not assume liability to the Recipient or third persons, nor will the Federal government reimburse or indemnify the Recipient for its liability due to any losses resulting in any way from the use of this data.

 

Requested citation format:

NOAA National Estuarine Research Reserve System (NERRS). System-wide Monitoring Program. Data accessed from the NOAA NERRS Centralized Data Management Office website: http://www.nerrsdata.org/; accessed 12 October 2012.

 

NERR water quality data and metadata can be obtained from the Research Coordinator at the individual NERR site (please see Principal Investigators and Contact Persons), from the Data Manager at the Centralized Data Management Office (please see personnel directory under the general information link on the CDMO home page) and online at the CDMO home page www.nerrsdata.org.  Data are available in comma delimited format.  

 
8)  Associated researchers and projects 
 

As part of the SWMP long-term monitoring program and in addition to water quality monitoring with YSI 6600 and EXO sondes, SFB NERR monitors 15-minute meteorological conditions at Rush Ranch and dissolved nutrients with monthly grab samples and diel sampling at all four sonde stations which may be correlated with this water quality dataset. These data are available at www.nerrsdata.org. Reserve staff also regularly monitors benthic invertebrates and marsh vegetation, with plans to expand these efforts over the coming years.

 
II.  Physical Structure Descriptors
 
9)  Sensor specifications 
 

SFB NERR deployed both 6600 and EXO series data sondes in 2018. Models in use: 4 x 6600 V2, and 7 x EXO2.  All sensor configurations were the same across sites and time. 6600 V2-4 sondes were always used at CC and at FM until 5/23/18, and EXO2 sondes were always used at GC, SM, and at FM starting 5/23/18. Both standard and wiped CT probes and guarded and unguarded pH probes were used with the EOX2 sondes. See Deployment Collection Period (Section 6) for specific configurations for each deployment.

Parameter: pH

Units: pH units

Sensor Type: Glass combination electrode

Model#: 599701(guarded) or 599702(wiped)

Range: 0 to 14 units

Accuracy: +/- 0.1 units within +/- 10° of calibration temperature, +/- 0.2 units for entire temperature range

Resolution: 0.01 units

 

Parameter: Turbidity

Units: formazin nephelometric units (FNU)

Sensor Type: Optical, 90 degree scatter

Model#: 599101-01

Range: 0 to 4000 FNU

Accuracy: 0 to 999 FNU: 0.3 FNU or +/-2% of reading (whichever is greater); 1000 to 4000 FNU +/-5% of reading

Resolution: 0 to 999 FNU: 0.01 FNU, 1000 to 4000 FNU: 0.1 FNU

 

Depth Qualifier:

The NERR System-Wide Monitoring Program utilizes YSI data sondes that can be equipped with either vented or non-vented depth/level sensors.  Readings for both vented and non-vented sensors are automatically compensated for water density change due to variations in temperature and salinity; but for all non-vented depth measurements, changes in atmospheric pressure between calibrations appear as changes in water depth.  The error is equal to approximately 1.02 cm for every 1 millibar change in atmospheric pressure, and is eliminated for vented sensors because they are vented to the atmosphere throughout the deployment time interval. 

 

Beginning in 2006, NERR SWMP standard calibration protocol calls for all non-vented depth sensors to read 0 meters at a (local) barometric pressure of 1013.25 mb (760 mm/hg).  To achieve this, each site calibrates their depth sensor with a depth offset number, which is calculated using the actual atmospheric pressure at the time of calibration and the equation provided in the SWMP calibration sheet or digital calibration log.  This offset procedure standardizes each depth calibration for the entire NERR System.  If accurate atmospheric pressure data are available, non-vented sensor depth measurements at any NERR can be corrected.

 

In 2010, the CDMO began automatically correcting depth/level data for changes in barometric pressure as measured by the Reserve’s associated meteorological station during data ingestion.  These corrected depth/level data are reported as cDepth and cLevel, and are assigned QAQC flags and codes based on QAQC protocols.  Please see sections 11 and 12 for QAQC flag and code definitions. 

 

NOTE:  older depth data cannot be corrected without verifying that the depth offset was in place and whether a vented or non-vented depth sensor was in use.  No SWMP data prior to 2006 can be corrected using this method.  The following equation is used for corrected depth/level data provided by the CDMO beginning in 2010:

((1013-BP)*0.0102)+Depth/Level = cDepth/cLevel.

 

Salinity Units Qualifier:

 

In 2013, EXO sondes were approved for SWMP use and began to be utilized by Reserves. While the 6600 series sondes report salinity in parts per thousand (ppt) units, the EXO sondes report practical salinity units (psu). These units are essentially the same and for SWMP purposes are understood to be equivalent, however psu is considered the more appropriate designation. Moving forward the NERR System will assign psu salinity units for all data regardless of sonde type.

 

Turbidity Qualifier:

 

In 2013, EXO sondes were approved for SWMP use and began to be utilized by Reserves. While the 6600 series sondes report turbidity in nephelometric turbidity units (NTU), the EXO sondes use formazin nephelometric units (FNU). These units are essentially the same but indicate a difference in sensor methodology, for SWMP purposes they will be considered equivalent.  Moving forward, the NERR System will use FNU/NTU as the designated units for all turbidity data regardless of sonde type. If turbidity units and sensor methodology are of concern, please see the Sensor Specifications portion of the metadata.

 

Chlorophyll Fluorescence Disclaimer:

YSI chlorophyll sensors (6025 or 599102-01) are designed to serve as a proxy for chlorophyll concentrations in the field for monitoring applications and complement traditional lab extraction methods; therefore, there are accuracy limitations associated with the data that are detailed in the YSI manual including interference from other fluorescent species, differences in calibration method, and effects of cell structure, particle size, organism type, temperature, and light on sensor measurements.

11)  QAQC flag definitions 
 
QAQC flags provide documentation of the data and are applied to individual data points by insertion into the parameter’s associated flag column (header preceded by an F_).   During primary automated QAQC (performed by the CDMO), -5, -4, and -2 flags are applied automatically to indicate data that is missing and above or below sensor range.  All remaining data are then flagged 0, passing initial QAQC checks.   During secondary and tertiary QAQC 1, -3, and 5 flags may be used to note data as suspect, rejected due to QAQC, or corrected.
 
-5 Outside High Sensor Range
-4 Outside Low Sensor Range
-3                Data Rejected due to QAQC
-2                Missing Data
-1                Optional SWMP Supported Parameter
 0                Data Passed Initial QAQC Checks
 1                Suspect Data
 2                Open - reserved for later flag
 3                Calculated data: non-vented depth/level sensor correction for changes in barometric pressure
 4                Historical Data:  Pre-Auto QAQC
 5                Corrected Data
 
12)  QAQC code definitions 
 
QAQC codes are used in conjunction with QAQC flags to provide further documentation of the data and are also applied by insertion into the associated flag column.  There are three (3) different code categories, general, sensor, and comment.  General errors document general problems with the deployment or YSI datasonde, sensor errors are sensor specific, and comment codes are used to further document conditions or a problem with the data.  Only one general or sensor error and one comment code can be applied to a particular data point, but some comment codes (marked with an * below) can be applied to the entire record in the F_Record column.  
 
General Errors

      GIC         No instrument deployed due to ice

      GIM        Instrument malfunction

      GIT         Instrument recording error; recovered telemetry data

      GMC       No instrument deployed due to maintenance/calibration

      GNF       Deployment tube clogged / no flow

      GOW      Out of water event

      GPF        Power failure / low battery

      GQR       Data rejected due to QA/QC checks

      GSM       See metadata

   Corrected Depth/Level Data Codes

      GCC        Calculated with data that were corrected during QA/QC

      GCM       Calculated value could not be determined due to missing data

      GCR        Calculated value could not be determined due to rejected data

      GCS        Calculated value suspect due to questionable data

      GCU       Calculated value could not be determined due to unavailable data

 

Sensor Errors

      SBO        Blocked optic

      SCF         Conductivity sensor failure

      SCS         Chlorophyll spike

      SDF        Depth port frozen

      SDG        Suspect due to sensor diagnostics

      SDO        DO suspect

      SDP        DO membrane puncture

      SIC          Incorrect calibration / contaminated standard

      SNV        Negative value

      SOW       Sensor out of water

      SPC         Post calibration out of range

      SQR        Data rejected due to QAQC checks

      SSD         Sensor drift

      SSM        Sensor malfunction

      SSR         Sensor removed / not deployed

      STF         Catastrophic temperature sensor failure

      STS         Turbidity spike

      SWM       Wiper malfunction / loss

 

Comments

      CAB*       Algal bloom

      CAF        Acceptable calibration/accuracy error of sensor

      CAP        Depth sensor in water, affected by atmospheric pressure

      CBF         Biofouling

      CCU        Cause unknown

      CDA*      DO hypoxia (<3 mg/L)

      CDB*      Disturbed bottom

      CDF        Data appear to fit conditions

      CFK*       Fish kill

      CIP *       Surface ice present at sample station

      CLT*       Low tide

      CMC*      In field maintenance/cleaning

      CMD*     Mud in probe guard

      CND       New deployment begins

      CRE*       Significant rain event

      CSM*      See metadata

      CTS         Turbidity spike

      CVT*       Possible vandalism/tampering

      CWD*     Data collected at wrong depth

      CWE*      Significant weather event

14)  Other remarks/notes 
 

Data are missing due to equipment or associated specific probes not being deployed, equipment failure, time of maintenance or calibration of equipment, or repair/replacement of a sampling station platform.  Any NANs in the dataset stand for “not a number” and are the result of low power, disconnected wires, or out of range readings.  If additional information on missing data is needed, contact the Research Coordinator at the reserve submitting the data.

 

China Camp

At very low tides the sonde at this site samples in an isolated puddle of water and sometimes comes out of water.

 

1/1 17:15 – 20:00, 1/2 17:30 – 20:30, 1/3 19:30 – 21:00, 1/4 20:30 – 21:15, 1/16 18:30, 1/17 18:45 – 19:30, 1/27 15:30 – 15:45, 1/28 15:30 – 17:45, 1/29 15:45 – 18:30, 1/30 16:30 – 19:30, 1/31 17:30 – 20:00, 2/1 18:15 – 20:45, 2/2 19:15 – 21:15, 2/15 18:15 – 19:15, 2/25 14:00 – 16:30, 2/26 15:00 – 17:15, 2/27 16:00 – 18:15, 2/28 16:45 – 19:00, 3/1 18:00 – 19:00, 3/26 14:00 – 15:30, 3/27 15:00 – 16:30, 3/28 16:00 – 17:00 4/17 6:45 – 8:15, 4/18 8:00 – 9:15, 4/19 8:30 – 10:00, 4/20 8:45 – 11:00, 4/21 10:15 – 12:00, 4/30 6:45 – 7:15, 5/1 7:15 – 7:45, 5/2 8:00, 5/3 8:30 – 9:15, 5/4 9:30 – 9:45, 5/5 5:45 – 7:15, 5/15 5:45 – 7:15, 5/16 6:00 – 8:15, 5/17 6:30 – 9:15, 5/18 7:30 – 10:15, 5/19 8:15 – 11:00, 5/20 9:30 – 12:00, 5/21 10:45 – 12:30, 5/28 5:45 – 6:15, 5/29 6:00 – 7:00, 5/30 6:30 – 7:45, 5/31 7:00 – 8:30, 6/1 7:45 – 9:15, 6/2 8:30 – 9:30, 6/3 9:00 – 10:00, 6/11 4:15 – 4:45, 6/12 4:30 – 6:15, 6/13 4:45 – 7:30, 6/14 5:30 – 8:15, 6/15 6:15 – 9:15, 6/16 7:15 – 10:00, 6/17 8:15 – 10:30, 6/18 9:45 – 11:15, 6/29 7:00 – 8:00, 6/30 7:30 – 8:30, 7/1 8:15 – 9:30, 7/11 4:15 – 6:00, 7/12 4:45 – 7:00, 7/13 5:15 – 8:00, 7/14 6:15 – 9:00, 7/15 7:00 – 9:30, 7/16 8:00 – 10:00, 8/8 3:30 – 4:15, 8/9 3:45 – 5:45, 8/10 4:30 – 6:45, 8/11 5:15 – 7:00, 8/12 6:15 – 8:00, 9/7 4:15 – 4:30, 9/8 4:30 – 6:00, 9/9 5:30 – 6:30 10/29 21:45 – 23:00, 11/7 18:15 – 18:30, 11/8 19:00 – 19:30, 11/9 19:15 – 20:15, 11/23 18:45, 11/24 18:45 – 20:30, 11/25 19:15 – 21:30, 11/26 20:15 – 22:15, 12/7 18:00 – 19:45, 12/8 18:45 – 20:15, 12/9 19:30 – 20:45, 12/20 17:00 – 17:15, 12/21 17:00 – 18:45, 12/22 17:15 – 19:45, 12/23 17:45 – 20:45, 12/24 19:00 – 21:15, 12/25 19:30 – 22:15, 12/26 20:15 – 23:00, 12/27 21:30 – 23:30 <-3> [SOW] (CSM), <1> [SNV] (CAP), or <1> [GSM] (CLT): Depth; <1> [GSM] (CLT): all other parameters. During these time periods, a puddle likely is forming or has formed around the sonde (as mentioned at the beginning of this section), appearing as flat-lined depth data in the dataset. The puddle usually forms below the depth port, and all other probes remain underwater. Small positive values within the error of the sensor are flagged when depth data are flat-lined; it is suspected that the depth port is out of water during these timepoints.

 

3/7/2018 8:30 – 4/1/2018 1:15 <1> [SPC] (CSM): pH, Turb. The batteries died on 4/1/2018. When the sonde was retrieved, the wiper was parked over the turbidity sensor optics; however, this appears to be due to the time at which the batteries died (mid-wipe) rather than a recurring issue during the deployment. Batteries had to be replaced in order to complete a post-check of the sonde, and voltage spikes occurred at this time and the turbidity and pH probes were malfunctioning while recording post-check values. Data appear to fit conditions for both of these parameters during the deployment up until the point of the batteries dying, so it is expected that the turbidity probe was causing voltage issues with the sonde that resulted in the batteries dying or after the batteries were changed.

 

6/10/2018 3:15 – 6/13/2018 6:45 <1> [GSM] (CBF): SpCond, Sal. Values seem lower than expected, and appear to return to normal following pipe cleaning on 6/13/2018 (see next comment). We believe the fouling impacting these values.

 

6/10/2018 3:15 – 6/13/2018 6:45 <1> [GSM] (CBF): Turbidity. Turbidity values also appear impacted by fouling prior to pipe cleaning on 6/13/2018 (see next comment).

 

6/13/2018 7:00 – 8:15 <-3> [GSM] (CMC): all parameters. The pipe was scrubbed during this time to remove biofouling build up.

 

10/2/2018 5:15 – 10/11/2018 6:30 <-3> [SSM] (CSM): pH. Multiple crabs were found in the sonde guard when the sonde was retrieved. The glass bulb on the sensor was cracked and broken, and it is suspected that this was caused by the crabs present in the guard. Because of this, the data from the earlier portion of the deployment prior to 10/2/2018 are not considered suspect.

 

11/22/2018 00:00 -11/28/2018 10:15 {CSM}. The sonde was deployed longer than the approved maximum deployment time of 28 days. The station was inaccessible due to heavy smoke in the region in November from the Camp Fire in Butte County, started 10/8/2018. The instrument was exchanged as soon as possible after smoke cleared from the region.

 

Gallinas Creek

6/21/18 11:45 – 7/18/18 9:45 {CSM}. The datasonde was set to record in time zone UTC-5 instead of UTC-8 (PST). The datetimestamps were adjusted by three hours to correct this in the .csv file that was uploaded to the CDMO. The dataset available from the CDMO contains the corrected datetimestamps, which differ from the raw .bin datafile archived for this site.

 

8/1/2018 00:00 – 8/15/2018 <1> [SPC] (CSM): pH. The pH sensor used during this deployment post-calibrated out of range (7.20 / 10.25), likely due to biofouling. However, the data appear normal and seam well with prior and following deployment data and the probe is in good working condition.

12/11/2018 09:15 - 12/31/2018 23:45 <0> (CSM): pH. Note that the pH probe died in the lab after deployment but prior to post-check in January 2019, so the post-check values are off due to a failed probe. However, the probe was working properly during the deployment and values are not considered suspect.

 

First Mallard

5/23/2018 11:00 <0> [GSM] (CND), {CSM}: all parameters. The 6600 series YSI data sondes were replaced at First Mallard by EXO series YSI data sondes as of this datetimestamp. See sensor specifications (Section 9). Of note, the depth transducer in the 6600 series is located 27.5 cm cm from the base of the sonde guard, and is located 21.4 cm from the base in the EXO. This results in a small jump in the depth data when the EXO was deployed, as water height over the depth transducer increased. This should be taken into account when evaluating the depth dataset when it crosses over this datetimestamp.

 

7/17/2018 10:30 – 8/14/18 8:30 {CSM}. The sonde was set to record every 15 minutes starting at 00:06:00 instead of 00:00:00. Consequently, the 15 minute points are offset by 6 minutes. The dataset available from the CDMO shows the standard fixed timepoints, but the raw datafiles archived with the CDMO reflect the true off set times.

 

8/2/2018 00:00 – 9/6/2018 23:45 {CSM}. The Suisun Marsh Salinity Control Gates operated by the CA Department of Water Resources in Montezuma Slough were placed in operation for this time period, which is outside of the usual season for operation activities. See CA DWR website for more information.

 

8/14/2018 9:00 – 9/11/2018 9:15 <1> [SPC] (CSM): pH. The pH sensor used during this deployment post-calibrated out of range (7.18 / 10.23), likely due to biofouling. However, the data appear normal and seam well with prior and following deployment data and the probe is in good working condition.

 

11/24/2018 00:00 -11/27/2018 11:00 {CSM}. The sonde was deployed longer than the approved maximum deployment time of 45 days. The station was inaccessible due to heavy smoke in the region in November from the Camp Fire in Butte County, started 10/8/2018. The instrument was exchanged as soon as possible after smoke cleared from the region.

 

12/12/2018 10:30 – 12/31/2018 23:45 <1> [SPC] (CSM): pH. The pH sensor used during this deployment post-calibrated out of range (7.13 / 10.28), possibly due to some mud buildup around the probes. However, the data appear normal and seam well with prior and following deployment data and the probe is in good working condition.

 

Second Mallard

6/20/18 11:30 – 7/17/18 10:45 {CSM}. The datasonde was set to record in time zone UTC-5 instead of UTC-8 (PST). The datetimestamps were adjusted by three hours to correct this in the .csv file that was uploaded to the CDMO. The dataset available from the CDMO contains the corrected datetimestamps, which differ from the raw .bin datafile archived for this site.

 

7/17/2018 11:00 – 8/14/18 9:00 {CSM}. The sonde was set to record every 15 minutes starting at 00:06:00 instead of 00:00:00. Consequently, the 15 minute points are off set by 6 minutes. The dataset available from the CDMO shows the standard fixed timepoints, but the raw datafiles archived with the CDMO reflect the true off set times.

 

8/2/2018 00:00 – 9/6/2018 23:45 {CSM}. The Suisun Marsh Salinity Control Gates operated by the CA Department of Water Resources in Montezuma Slough were placed in operation for this time period, which is outside of the usual season for operation activities. See CA DWR website for more information.

 

11/24/2018 00:00 -11/27/2018 10:15 {CSM}. The sonde was deployed longer than the approved maximum deployment time of 45 days. The station was inaccessible due to heavy smoke in the region in November from the Camp Fire in Butte County, started 10/8/2018. The instrument was exchanged as soon as possible after smoke cleared from the region.
